<br>
Offensively, if if a pet does 10dps/m(damage/second /mana), and a DoT spell does 10dps/m, you aboslutely want the DoT when forced to choose. Why? The DoT doesn't die.<br>
<br>
What I'm saying is, the offense and defense of the mage class being rolled into 1 thing (the pet) is a bad thing.<br>
<br>
So now consider this, you have 2 pets, an offensive pet and a defensive pet. The offensive one cannot take hits but thus cannot die. The defensive one does nothing but take all the agro. It can die, but can't deal dmg.<br>
<br>
Now compare this defensive pet to root. You still think pet &gt; root? WRONG. Root can last a long time. It lasts longer than a pet, that's for sure. Only time it's as crappy as some people would have you believe is when they're fighting mobs too hard for them. Root on a low blue will almost always last full duration. If they're level 30 fighting yellows, duh it breaks in 12 seconds.<br>
<br>
================<br>
Personally, as long as our offensive capabilities do match our lack of defensive/escape abilities, I'm happy not having root.<br>
================<br>
<br>
The entire premise and purpose of this argument is that your argument may no longer be valid.<br>
<br>
Clerics = defensive.. Now have offense.<br>
<br>
So how come mage = offense, still have the worst defense?<br>
<br>
If the <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> intra</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->-class balance* issue no longer applies to clerics, why us?<br>
<br>
*Balance within one's own class.<br>
